    hero_caption: "<p>Bill Frisell. Photo by Paul Moore. </p>",
    short_description:
      "<p>Acclaimed guitarist Bill Frisell explores early American folk music in this solo performance, presented on the occasion of the exhibition <em>PHOTOGRAPHY + FOLK ART: Looking for America in the 1930s</em>.</p><p>If this program reaches capacity, a stand-by line will form outside of the auditorium entrance at 7:00 for seats that become available.</p>",
    header_description: null,
    list_description: "<p>Live Arts program</p>",
    description:
      '<p>Acclaimed guitarist Bill Frisell explores early American folk music in this solo performance, presented on the occasion of the exhibition<em> </em><a href="/exhibitions/9202/photography-folk-art-looking-for-america-in-the-1930s" target="_blank"><em>PHOTOGRAPHY + FOLK ART: Looking for America in the 1930s</em></a>.</p><p><strong>About the Artist</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Bill Frisell’s career as a guitarist and composer has spanned more than 40 years and many celebrated recordings. <em>DownBeat Magazine</em> cites his catalog as "the best recorded output of the decade." The<em> Chicago Reader</em> says his latest album of original songs, Music IS for Okeh/Sony, “beautifully encapsulates Frisell’s depth and range in all its meditative glory." And the <em>New York Times</em> calls him “one of the most distinctive and original improvising artists of our time.”</p><p>Recognized as one of America’s 21 most vital and productive performing artists, Frisell was named an inaugural Doris Duke Artist in 2012 and is the recipient of grants from United States Artists. In 2016, he was a beneficiary of the first FreshGrass Composition Commission to preserve and support innovative grassroots music. He served as one of the original Resident Artistic Directors of San Francisco Jazz and is the subject of a new documentary film by Emma Franz entitled <em>Bill Frisell: A Portrait</em>, which examines his creative process in depth.</p><p>Persons with disabilities who would like to request an accessibility accommodation for an Art Institute program are encouraged to send an email to <a href=" access@artic.edu">access@artic.edu</a> two weeks in advance of the program.&nbsp;</p>',
